---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Methodology" lang="en">
  <article class="prose-page">
    <h1>Methodology</h1>

    <p class="lead">
      Transparency about the content creation process is a core principle of Medienrechtspraxis.
      This page documents how content is generated, evaluated, and updated.
    </p>

    <h2>AI-Powered Content Generation</h2>
    <p>
      Content is generated using Claude (Anthropic). For each topic and content layer,
      a specialised prompt is constructed incorporating statute texts retrieved via the
      opencaselaw MCP, leading cases from the Federal Supreme Court and ECtHR identified
      through the case law database, scholarly commentaries from OnlineKommentar.ch as
      reference material, and topic-specific guidelines controlling structure, depth, and
      comparative perspectives.
    </p>

    <h2>Quality Assurance</h2>
    <p>
      Every generated piece of content undergoes automated quality evaluation by an
      evaluator agent.
    </p>

    <h3>Five Non-Negotiable Requirements (all must pass)</h3>
    <p>
      Factual accuracy of all legal statements. Correct citation of all decisions and
      sources. No hallucinated cases — zero tolerance. Proper attribution of DACH
      comparative references. Language quality (grammar, terminology, register).
    </p>

    <h3>Five Scored Dimensions (1–5 each, minimum 3)</h3>
    <p>
      Analytical depth, completeness, practical value, source quality, readability.
    </p>
    <p>
      If content fails evaluation, it is regenerated with the evaluator's feedback
      (up to three attempts). If the third attempt also fails, the content is flagged
      for manual review.
    </p>

    <h2>Daily Updates</h2>
    <p>
      Every night, an automated process (GitHub Actions) checks for newly published
      relevant court decisions via the opencaselaw API. When new decisions are identified,
      affected topics are automatically updated — the case law layer is regenerated, and
      for leading cases the update cascades to the doctrine and practice layers.
    </p>

    <h2>Translation</h2>
    <p>
      The English version is automatically translated from the German original. Legal
      terminology is translated with the original term in parentheses on first occurrence.
      Citations and statute references remain in their original form.
    </p>

    <h2>Data Sources</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>opencaselaw.ch:</strong> Swiss Federal Supreme Court decisions, statute texts,
      scholarly commentaries (OnlineKommentar.ch, CC-BY-4.0).
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Anthropic Claude:</strong> Language model for content generation, evaluation,
      and translation.
    </p>

    <h2>Limitations</h2>
    <p>
      AI-generated content may contain errors despite quality assurance. Automated evaluation
      reduces but does not eliminate all risks. Hallucinated decisions are strictly checked
      but cannot be excluded with absolute certainty. DACH comparisons do not claim to be
      exhaustive. The content does not replace professional legal advice.
    </p>

    <h2>Source Code</h2>
    <p>
      The complete code — pipeline, website, MCP server — is openly available on
      <a href="https://github.com/medienrechtspraxis/medienrechtspraxis">GitHub</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .prose-page {
    max-width: var(--width-content);
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .prose-page h1 {
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-lg);
  }

  .lead {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-xl);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
</style>
